metadata.name: MoodColors #99
metadata.description: The artwork is based on principles of Orphism and Bauhaus , as one of the most striking examples of a combination of functionality, simplicity and at the same time the ability to convey the underlying meaning, where the form is determined by function. Where color is one of the most important values. Our goal is to visualize all the richness and versatility of human emotions with the help of color. What, if not color, is able to convey the whole gamut of feelings and experiences that we experience.  Every bright event in our life, both positive and negative, always leaves its mark in our memory. We show it through lines – it's like wrinkles on the face, marks of the experience, like a note on a sheet, a dash / tick, like an entry in the diary of life, where the sheet on which we made a note is colored in the color of emotions and sensations that we experienced again and again. It's always a lot of mixed shades that have their own unique palette.  The fundamental emotions and feelings such as anger, sadness, fear, disgust, joy and love are taken. Each token is one emotion, where with the help of color we show how multifaceted it can be.

metadata.name: Rearranged #20
metadata.description:
Rearranged is an invitation to engage in an exploration of aesthetics within the constraints of the generated token. 

Each piece has 4 layers. Each layer can be independently rotated by 90 degrees clockwise by clicking 1,2,3 or 4 on the keyboard. Some changes are subtle. Some are surprising. 

's' on the keyboard will scramble all of the rotations.
'r' will reset to the original artwork.

You are invited to: 
arrange a more aesthetically pleasing piece than the original;
scramble the artwork and use the number keys to return it to its original state;
work out which shapes have been erased from each layer.

And of course there is also a gorgeous gradient illusion made of solid-colour filled tessellating shapes. 

3 tessellations of varying sizes, 12 layouts with random elements, 14 palettes.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Field Conditions #19
metadata.description:
Manual architectural drafting is thrilling. 

The precise control of the drafting mayline, protractor, and technical pen contrasts with the spontaneous, willful hand drawn line.

These drawings feel simultaneously mechanical and free.

This project was inspired by Lebbeus Woods's "Conflict Space 3", but I found myself also referencing the work of Allan Jacobs, particularly his beautiful book "Great Streets", and Marion Mahony, a long-time drafter for Frank Lloyd Wright. 

Relative size of marks, overlapping, and relative density all enhance the illusion of depth without actually modeling a 3-D space. I like how this small set of line styles can evoke so many different kinds of imagery and scales: viral particles, confetti, accelerating to light speed, contrails, cities at night, a camp fire, snow falling...

metadata.name: Celestial Objects #94
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #297
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd
